  <static seed="1328" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/divideRationalExpressions25.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{({4x+4}) \div ({8x+8}) =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{1}{2}, x\ne -1</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   ({4x+4}) \div ({8x+8}) 
      \amp = \frac{{4x+4}}{1} \div \frac{{8x+8}}{1} \\
      \amp = \frac{{4x+4}}{1} \cdot {\frac{1}{8x+8}} \\
      \amp = \frac{{4\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}}{1} \cdot \frac{1}{{8\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{1}{2}, x\ne -1}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>x+1</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification are <m>x \ne {-1}</m>.</p>
</solution>
